BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:White Evangelicalism: Unpacking the movement's history
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260326T190000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260326T210000
UID:260218OeRsR5lAI06zXvFpVyTbyg
DESCRIPTION:White Evangelicalism: Unpacking the movement’s history in or
 der to understand its influence on the country and culture today\n\nThursd
 ay\, March 26\, 7:00 pm\n\nThe Iona Lecture Series is where arts and scien
 ces meet humanity. In this Iona Lecture\, public theologian Cara Meredith 
 will trace the history of the white evangelical movement\, particularly in
  the 20th century\, in order to understand its influence on U.S. politics 
 and culture today. Her work highlights both the harm and the good\, partic
 ularly toward women\, people of color\, and the LGBTQ\\+ community\, and i
 s told through a storytelling lens of personal narrative\, Christian theol
 ogy\, and journalistic integrity.  \n\nJoin us for this important evenin
 g of conversation with lecture at 7 pm and wine and cheese reception to fo
 llow. \n\nFree and Open to the Public. \n\nAuthor\, freelance writer\, a
 nd public theologian Cara Meredith is passionate about collective liberati
 on\, mutual reciprocity\, and being a good neighbor. Her first book\, The 
 Color of Life: A Journey Toward Love and Racial Justice \\(Zondervan\, 201
 9\\)\, examines her journey as a white woman into issues of race after mar
 rying the son of Civil Rights icon James Meredith. Her second book\, Churc
 h Camp: Bad Skits\, Cry Night\, and How White Evangelicalism Betrayed a Ge
 neration \\(Broadleaf\, 2025\\)\, lends a critical eye to the place she lo
 ved and long called home\, with a particular lens toward injustices experi
 enced by women\, people of color\, and the LGBTQ\\+ community. She holds a
  master of theology from Fuller Seminary and is a postulant for Holy Order
 s in the Episcopal Church \\(Diocese of California\\)\, to be ordained Dea
 con in June 2026 and Priest in December 2026. With a background in educati
 on and nonprofit work\, she wears more hats than she probably ought\, but 
 mostly just enjoys playing with words\, a lot. She has been featured in na
 tional media outlets such as The Oregonian\, The New York Times\, The Livi
 ng Church\, The Christian Century\, and Baptist News Global\, among others
 . The Pacific Northwest native now lives in the San Francisco Bay Area wit
 h her husband and two sons.
LOCATION:St. Columba's Inverness
URL:https://www.stcolumbasinverness.org/iona-lecture-cara-meredith
X-SOURCE:North Bay Bohemian
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:St. Joseph's Table and Italian Dinner
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260326T170000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260326T200000
UID:260324lN_rZygscUWA4aRtAAjg3g
DESCRIPTION:The North Bay Italian Cultural Foundation invites you to Join 
 us for a pasta and meatballs dinner and a St. Joseph's Table. Your choice 
 of marinara or pesto penne\, Mamma Rosa's special meatballs\, breadsticks 
 and a Classico Caesar Salad with shaved parmigiano. Catered by Cibo Rustic
 o Pizzeria.\n\nAntipasti\, dessert and wine at the table. Open bar for pur
 chase.\n\nAnd live music by Carlo Solivan.\n\nThere will be a St. Joseph's
  Table. For Italian families\, St. Joseph's Day \\(March 19\, but we will 
 be celebrating at our dinner\\) serves as a means to preserve culture\, va
 lues\, and traditions. It unites generations\, keeps recipes and stories a
 live\, and strengthens community bonds. Over time\, it has evolved into on
 e of the most significant cultural celebrations among Italian communities 
 worldwide. Traditionally\, St. Joseph's Tables are open to all\, ensuring 
 that no one is turned away\, and leftover food is shared with those in nee
 d. The North Bay Italian Cultural Foundation was built on a foundation of 
 Italian heritage and community. Our St. Joseph's Dinner on March 26th cont
 inues this legacy by bringing people together through food\, music\, and c
 elebration. It honors our roots\, welcomes new generations\, and shares ou
 r culture with the broader community. You don't have to be Italian to join
 \; everyone is welcome.\n\nGiving food to the needy is customary on St. Jo
 seph’s Day. If you are attending the dinner\, please consider bringing a
  non-perishable item\\(s\\) to donate to a local food bank.
LOCATION:Sonoma County Veterans Memorial Center
URL:https://nbicf.org/
X-SOURCE:North Bay Bohemian
END:VEVENT
