BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:"Standin' In a Hard Rain" Interview and Q&A with Author/Activist J
 oel Eis
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260326T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260326T200000
UID:260318GvZr6_1je0Ku80h2-BrRFA
DESCRIPTION:On Thursday March 26 at 6:30pm the San Geronimo Valley Commu
 nity Center's Valley Arts and Lectures Series will host author/activist Jo
 el Eis in conversation with Albert Flynn DeSilver. Eis claims to have beco
 me an activist “in utero” and his mothers refusal to cross a picket li
 ne when he was a child didn’t seem like a radical move\, it’s just how
  he was raised.  He often says his life's path was laid out\, often\, by 
 circumstances out of his own control. In his own words Eis says\, “Stand
 in' in a Hard Rain draws on my knack for being in the right place at the 
 right time. As a result of forces over which I had no control I was not on
 ly on the front lines and in the streets\, but in the room for planning so
 me of the major events of the 1960's.” \n\n Eis was present at many “
 inflection” points in the 60’s & 70’s. He was a part of the Freedom 
 Riders in the Deep South\, the Strike of '68 at S.F. State University \\(t
 he longest\, most violent student strike in American History\, the Draft R
 esistance with David Harris and Joan Baez\, the Grape Strike with Caesar C
 havez\, Angela Davis\, Eldridge Cleaver and the Panthers. He even faced a 
 bayonet at his own throat from the National Guard at Berkeley’s People
 ’s Park. He also used his training as an actor\, director\, and designer
  in important radical and progressive theatre companies for progressive ch
 ange. This put him in front of the crowd and backstage with the makers of 
 ideas.\n\nIn 2023\, after much encouragement from those who had been regal
 ed with his many stories\, he wrote his memoir “Standin’ in a Hard Ra
 in”. It turns out its release couldn’t have been more timely. I had t
 he thought that when he was writing his memoir\, Eis could not have imagin
 ed we would be where we are right now as a country …or maybe he did.   
 Although we are in unprecedented times\, there is a lot to be learned from
  this generation about what it takes to protect Civil Rights and Democracy
 . Please join us for this special event.
LOCATION:San Geronimo Valley Community Center
URL:https://sgvperformingarts.eventcalendarapp.com/interview-and-qanda-wit
 h-authoractivist-joel-eis
X-SOURCE:North Bay Bohemian
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Portuguese Cooking Class with Chef Antelmo Faria
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260326T170000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260326T193000
UID:260318CC_dmHZzhEa82gAczzkn_Q
DESCRIPTION:Portuguese Cooking Class with Chef Antelmo Faria - March 26\n\
 n$125.00\n\nJoin Sonoma Family Meal and chef Antelmo Faria for a cooking c
 lass at the Sonoma Family Meal Kitchen with an eye toward traditional old 
 world Portuguese flavors and a nod to local California cuisine.\n\nThe han
 ds-on\, collaborative class will last 2.5 hours\, with time to enjoy your 
 meal together at the end. Whether you’re a seasoned cook or just startin
 g out\, this class will offer a fun\, engaging learning environment\, whil
 e raising funds for Sonoma Family Meal’s free culinary job training and 
 food-security programs.\n\nIf you haven’t been to the SFM Kitchen yet\, 
 this class is also the perfect chance to visit and experience where the ma
 gic takes place and how the work gets done.\n\nWHEN: Thursday March 26th\,
  5-7:30pm WHERE: SFM community kitchen\, 1370A Redwood Way\, Petaluma\n\nT
 HE MENU:\n\nAppetizer: Caldo verde - a popular\, rustic Portuguese soup fe
 aturing a creamy potato base\, thinly sliced leafy greens\, garlic\, onion
 s\, and olive oil\n\nMain: Piri Piri Chicken - tender smoky chicken marina
 ted in a spicy\, vibrant sauce made from African bird's eye chilies\, garl
 ic\, lemon juice\, oil\, and herbs\n\nSide: Algarf Carrots - lemon zest\, 
 cilantro\, cumin roasted carrots from the Algarf region of Portugal\n\nSid
 e: Salsa Verde Roasted Potatoes\n\nDessert: Orange Olive Oil Cake\n\nBYOB:
  Bring Your Own Beverage\n\nIf you have a specific food allergy or have an
 y questions about the menu\, please contact hannah@sonomafamilymeal.org.\n
 \nABOUT THE CHEF:\n\nChef Telmo Faria\, was born in the Bay Area\, Califor
 nia to Portuguese immigrant parents\, who moved back to the island of Faia
 l in the Azores when he was only a year old. Chef Telmo's first restaurant
  experience came when his father opened 'Adega Santa' in Horta\, Faial. It
  was there that his love of cooking and hospitality was forged. He recalls
  daily shopping trips with his father to the small seasonal produce stalls
  of the local outdoor market\, purchasing fresh fish directly from fisherm
 en at the city's docks\, and visiting butchers selling local\, sustainably
  raised meats.\n\nEventually returning to California\, Chef Telmo enrolled
  at the California Culinary Academy in San Francisco. He has since spent t
 he last 20 years honing his craft and refining his skills in the kitchens 
 of LaSalette Restaurant \\(Sonoma\, CA\\)\, Montrio Bistro \\(Monterey\, C
 A\\)\, as the Executive Chef for the TMI restaurant group \\(Tacolicious\,
  Mosto\\)\, and the last 9 years as the Executive Chef/Owner of the michel
 in-rated UMA CASA Portuguese restaurant in San Francisco. His restaurant U
 ma Casa was even featured on Check Please! Bay Area on KQED\, Good Morning
  America\, CBS News Bay Area KPIX\, The San Francisco Chronicle\, Forbes\,
 Williams Sonoma\, and more!\n\nChef Telmo is a published cookbook author\,
  has consulted on multiple local and international restaurant concepts\, p
 articipated in marquee food and wine festivals\, as well as making numerou
 s local\, national\, and international television appearances.\n\nChef Tel
 mo's goal is to use the inspirations of his childhood and heritage to brin
 g diners the flavors of Portugal\, using the sensibilities and sourcing pr
 actices that have become synonymous with the California dining landscape.
LOCATION:Sonoma Family Meal Kitchen
URL:https://www.sonomafamilymeal.org/store-2/portuguesecooking
X-SOURCE:North Bay Bohemian
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:What About Age? Art Exhibit
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260326T090000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260326T180000
UID:2603183ZXH03wgOk--rTjqv3gSNg
DESCRIPTION:*What About Age?* art exhibit has arrived in Marin County! Or
 iginally displayed at NYU’s Kimmel Windows\, this exhibit explores ageis
 m through contemporary art\, featuring works by both local youth and senio
 r artists.\n\n*What About Age?* is an art exhibit and educational initiat
 ive designed to challenge stereotypes about aging\, address ageism and soc
 ial isolation\, and promote intergenerational dialogue through the lens of
  art.\n\nIn partnership with Youth in Arts\, the exhibit features artworks
  by local youth and senior artists\, showcasing how age intersects with cr
 eativity\, identity\, and experience. Under the guidance of Youth in Arts\
 , these emerging and established artists work side by side to create colla
 borative pieces\, fostering meaningful connections between generations and
  reflecting the exhibit’s core message: art is ageless.\n\nThe exhibit a
 lso includes artwork panels by New York-based writer and illustrator Aubre
 y Hirsch\, first displayed at NYU’s Kimmel Windows and originally organi
 zed by Stacey Gordon\, NYU’s Program Director of Next Phase Adult Caregi
 ving and Retirement at Work Life.\n\nThe new exhibition will be on view at
  the Marin County Civic Center galleries from January 26 to May 6\, 2026. 
 Works will be displayed on the first and third floor exhibits\, Monday to 
 Friday from 9 a.m. to 6 p.m.\n\nThe *What About Age?* art exhibit is prese
 nted by Marin Cultural Association in partnership with Marin Community Fou
 ndation and Youth in Arts. Beyond the art exhibit\, the *What About Age?* 
 initiative offers programming\, led by Vivalon\, designed to challenge age
 ism and provide resources for Marin County's growing aging population.
LOCATION:Marin County Civic Center
URL:https://www.marincultural.org/exhibitions
X-SOURCE:North Bay Bohemian
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Samba no Pé - First Class
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260326T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260326T193000
UID:260317JOFdTdGQMkiib5l3YoyqLQ
DESCRIPTION:Get ready to feel the rhythm and energy of Rio de Janeiro! Sa
 mba no Pé \\(Samba in the Foot\\) is the captivating solo style of samba
  danced in the streets and at Carnival\, known for its rapid\, intricate f
 ootwork and infectious hip movements.\n\nYou will learn\n\nThe Basic Step:
  You will master the signature quick-quick-slow rhythm that defines Samba 
 no Pé.\n\nArm & Hip Styling: You will learn how to add the authentic flai
 r\, movement\, and energy that makes Brazilian samba so captivating.\n\nTe
 chnique & Posture: You will receive tips on proper body alignment to help 
 you dance longer\, faster\, and more safely.\n\nRhythm & Musicality: You w
 ill learn how to connect your movement directly to the irresistible beat o
 f the bateria \\(the samba drum section\\).\n\nThis class is perfect for a
 nyone looking to connect with the vibrant spirit of Brazil\, improve coord
 ination\, and get a fantastic workout—all while learning the foundationa
 l steps of this iconic dance. No partner or prior dance experience is requ
 ired! Just bring your enthusiasm and comfortable shoes!\n\nDate & Time: Th
 ursdays @6:30PM – 7:30PM\n\nAddress: 4140 Redwood Highway \\#8 San Rafae
 l\, CA\n\nNote: Arrive 10 minutes before. No floor marking shoe soles allo
 wed.
LOCATION:4140 Redwood Highway #8 • San Rafael
URL:https://salsadancemarin.com/samba-no-pe
X-SOURCE:North Bay Bohemian
END:VEVENT
